{"parse":{"title":"Dolgopolsky list","pageid":29138511,"revid":660864553,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Dolgopolsky list</b> is a word list compiled by <a href=\"/wiki/Aharon_Dolgopolsky\" title=\"Aharon Dolgopolsky\">Aharon Dolgopolsky</a> in 1964. It lists the 15 lexical items that have the most semantic stability, i.e. they are the 15 words least likely to be replaced by other words as a language evolves. It was based on a study of 140 languages from across <a href=\"/wiki/Eurasia\" title=\"Eurasia\">Eurasia</a>.\n</p><p>The words, with the first being the most stable, are:\n</p>\n<ol><li>I/me</li>\n<li>two/pair</li>\n<li>you (singular, informal)</li>\n<li>who/what</li>\n<li>tongue</li>\n<li>name</li>\n<li>eye</li>\n<li>heart</li>\n<li>tooth</li>\n<li>no/not</li>\n<li>nail (finger-nail)</li>\n<li>louse/nit</li>\n<li>tear/teardrop</li>\n<li>water</li>\n<li>dead</li></ol>\n<p>The first item in the list, <i>I/me</i>, has been replaced in none of the 140 languages during their recorded history; the fifteenth, <i>dead</i>, has been replaced in 25% of the languages.\n</p><p>The twelfth item, <i>louse/nit</i>, is well kept in the North Caucasian languages, Dravidian and Turkic, but not in other proto-languages.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dolgopolsky_list&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Swadesh_list\" title=\"Swadesh list\">Swadesh list</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dolgopolsky_list&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul>